I think that using `TreeSet` is going to be your best option, as per the [constructor documentation][1] the default ordering is the natural ordering of the elements. With your specific pseudo-code example (using `Integer`s) this will work pretty much perfectly:

```
var set1 = new TreeSet&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(
  11, 13, 24, 14, 25, 15, 26, 16, 
  27, 28, 18, 19, 1, 2, 3, 6
)); 
System.out.println(set1);
```

```
[1, 2, 3, 6, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28]
```

If, however, you are using `String`s, then lexical ordering is used, as that&#39;s the natural ordering for that type:

```
var set2 = new TreeSet&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(
  &quot;11&quot;, &quot;13&quot;, &quot;24&quot;, &quot;14&quot;, &quot;25&quot;, &quot;15&quot;, &quot;26&quot;, &quot;16&quot;,
  &quot;27&quot;, &quot;28&quot;, &quot;18&quot;, &quot;19&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;2&quot;, &quot;3&quot;, &quot;6&quot; 
)); 
System.out.println(set2);
```

```
[1, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19, 2, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28, 3, 6]
```

You have the option of providing a [`Comparator`][2] to [one of the constructors][3] to allow you to customise the ordering to your liking:

```
var set3 = new TreeSet&lt;&gt;((String a, String b) -&gt; {
  return Integer.valueOf(a).compareTo(Integer.valueOf(b));
}); 
set3.addAll(Arrays.asList(
  &quot;11&quot;, &quot;13&quot;, &quot;24&quot;, &quot;14&quot;, &quot;25&quot;, &quot;15&quot;, &quot;26&quot;, &quot;16&quot;,
  &quot;27&quot;, &quot;28&quot;, &quot;18&quot;, &quot;19&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;2&quot;, &quot;3&quot;, &quot;6&quot; 
)); 
System.out.println(set3);
```

```
[1, 2, 3, 6, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28]
```

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/16/docs/api/java.base/java/util/TreeSet.html#%3Cinit%3E()
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/16/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Comparator.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/16/docs/api/java.base/java/util/TreeSet.html#%3Cinit%3E(java.util.Comparator)

